Second, RNA is usually single-stranded, while DNA is double-stranded.

Transcription is carried out by an enzyme called RNA polymerase. RNA polymerase binds to a specific region of DNA called the promoter. The promoter is a sequence of DNA that tells RNA polymerase where to start transcribing. Once RNA polymerase has bound to the promoter, it begins to unwind the DNA double helix. RNA polymerase then uses one strand of the DNA as a template to create a complementary RNA strand.

The process of transcription is continuous, meaning that RNA polymerase does not stop and start again. Instead, it moves along the DNA template, adding nucleotides to the growing RNA strand one at a time. When RNA polymerase reaches the end of the gene, it releases the RNA strand and the DNA double helix reforms.

The RNA that is produced by transcription is called messenger RNA (mRNA). mRNA is then transported out of the nucleus and into the cytoplasm. In the cytoplasm, mRNA is translated into protein.
